Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{1/2%tsp} for the linguine.

Zest and halve the @lemon{1}. Roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1}(stalks and all).

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @echalion shallot{1}.

Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

When your pan of water is boiling, add the @linguine{180%g} and bring back to the boil.
Cook until tender, ~{12%minutes}.

Once cooked, reserve some of the pasta water, then drain in a #colander{}.

Pop the linguine back in the pan. Drizzle with @oil{drizzle} and stir through to stop it from sticking together.

While the pasta cooks, heat a drizzle of oil in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the shallot and cook, stirring frequently, until softened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Stir in the garlic and cook for ~{1%minute} more.

Pour in the @reserved pasta water{100%ml} and @vegetable stock paste{10%g}, stir together, then bring to the boil. Simmer for ~{3-4%minutes}.

Stir the @king prawns{300%g}(raw) and @peas{120%g} into the sauce and cook for another ~{5-6%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw prawns. The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Once the prawns are cooked, stir the @creme fraiche{75%g} and lemon zest into the sauce. Bring back to the boil, then remove from the heat.

Season with @black pepper{}, then stir through the cooked pasta and half the parsley.

Add a squeeze of lemon juice. Taste and season with salt, pepper and more lemon juice if needed.

When ready, share the prawn linguine between your #bowls{}.

Sprinkle with the remaining parsley, then serve with any remaining lemon cut into wedges for squeezing over. Enjoy!